# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bk-chicken-fries
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The 2013 horsemeat scandal was a food fraud crisis that began on 15 January 2013 when it was reported that a wide range of food products advertised in the European Union as containing beef were found to contain undeclared or improperly declared horse meat.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The crisis escalated in February 2013 when some Findus products were found to contain up to 100% horsemeat instead of beef.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] A smaller number of products also contained other undeclared meats, such as pork.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The issue was discovered through DNA testing on frozen beefburgers and lasagne sold in several Irish and British supermarkets.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The analysis found that 23 out of 27 beef burger samples also contained pig DNA.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Adherents of some religions are forbidden from eating pork or horse meat due to their beliefs.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] While the presence of undeclared meat was not a health issue, the scandal revealed a major breakdown in the traceability of the food supply chain and the risk that harmful ingredients could have been included.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Sports horses, for example, could have entered the food supply chain, and with them the veterinary drug phenylbutazone, which is banned in food animals.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The scandal later spread to 13 other European countries, and European authorities decided to find an EU-wide solution.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] They initiated meat testing of about 4,000 horse meat samples for the veterinary drug.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Investigations by the Food Safety Authority of Ireland (FSAI) led Ireland to become the first EU state to report the presence of horse meat in beef and to make the results public.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The first positive test for equine DNA was on 10 December 2012.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] It carried out additional tests on 18 and 21 December.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The FSAI then sent samples to the Eurofins laboratory in Germany.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Professor Alan Reilly of the FSAI testified to the Oireachtas on 5 February 2013 that the results indicated the presence of equine DNA, but not the amount.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The IdentiGen Laboratory and the Eurofins Laboratory were asked to determine the amount of horse meat in the samples.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 21 December 2012, the FSAI requested that the Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine in Ireland obtain further samples.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] These were sent to the IdentiGen laboratory on 4 January 2013.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Results were received back from Eurofins and IdentiGen on 11 January 2013.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Professor Reilly reported on 5 February that quantitative results from IdentiGen were received by the FSAI late on the evening of 11 January 2013.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Of the ten burger products that tested positive for equine DNA, all but one were at low levels.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The quantification of equine DNA in this burger product estimated 29% relative to the beef DNA content.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Silvercrest manufactured this product on behalf of Tesco.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] At this point, there was no explanation for the finding of 29% equine DNA relative to beef DNA in this single sample.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 14 January 2013, the FSAI informed the Department of Health and the Department of Agriculture, Food and the Marine of the final results.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On the same day, it also informed the Food Standards Agency in the United Kingdom.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The next day, 15 January 2013, the FSAI advised the five retailers concerned, Tesco, Dunnes Stores, Aldi, Lidl and Iceland, of their findings; all these firms withdrew the offending products.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The media and newspapers of 16 January 2013 led with the story, focusing on the one burger which tested positive for 29% equine DNA.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Another significant investigation into the horse meat affair in Ireland, by Ireland's Department of Agriculture, published its findings in March 2013.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In the UK, a House of Commons Select Committee on Environment, Food and Rural Affairs report on the horse meat incident was not critical of UK or Irish producers.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] It expressed concern that horsemeat contamination resulted from fraud and other criminal activity across the EU.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The second major UK report on the horse meat incident was conducted by Professor Chris Elliott, the Director of the Institute for Global Food Security at Queen's University Belfast.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In his independent report, he argues that food crime was at the heart of the horsemeat incident and makes a range of suggestions for how this could be tackled.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Of 27 beef burger products tested, 37% were positive for horse DNA, and 85% were positive for pig DNA.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Of 31 beef meal products tested, 21 were positive for pig DNA, but all were negative for horse DNA.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Nineteen salami products were tested, but were negative for all foreign DNA.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Of the 37% of beef products tested positive for horse DNA, Tesco's Everyday Value Beef Burgers tested at 29.1%.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] All other reported brands had less than 0.3% horse DNA.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] These products originated from Liffey Meats and Silvercrest Foods in Ireland, and from the Dalepak Hambleton food processing plant in the United Kingdom.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Trace amounts of horse DNA were also found in raw ingredients imported from Spain and the Netherlands.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Laboratory DNA investigations were requested by the authorities into possible donkey meat adulteration of minced meat products labelled as 100% beef.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] British company Primerdesign provided many of the tests to laboratories and companies wishing to test for contamination.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] By 16 January 2013, four subsidiaries of ABP Food Group had been accused of supplying adulterated meat.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] They were Silvercrest in County Monaghan, Dalepak in North Yorkshire, Freshlink in Glasgow, ABP Nenagh in County Tipperary, Ireland, and Dairy Crest, Rossington.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Hamburger meat from Silvercrest Foods, a subsidiary of Larry Goodman's ABP Food Group, in County Monaghan, Ireland, was found to contain 29% horse meat relative to beef.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Tesco dropped Silvercrest as a supplier of processed meat, but ABP said that it "welcomed their decision to continue sourcing fresh beef from other ABP companies".
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The first apparent instance of fresh beef being adulterated with horse meat was reported by Asda, which removed its 500-gram own-label beef Bolognese sauce from sale.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The sauce was supplied by Greencore, which said in a statement that the meat in the sauce had been supplied by ABP Food Group's Nenagh plant in County Tipperary, Ireland.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Burger King, which had more than 500 fast food outlets in Ireland and the UK at the time, dropped Silvercrest as a supplier, using suppliers in Germany and Italy instead, after horse meat was found in their supply chain.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Waitrose removed beef meatballs from sale when it found that they contained pork.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The meatballs were manufactured by an ABP factory in Glasgow.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Waitrose, part of John Lewis, said it would be creating a new facility to supply its own beef products.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Tesco, the Co-operative Group, Iceland, and Aldi also cancelled their contracts with ABP Food Group due to the adulteration.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Food wholesaler Makro, supplier to the restaurant and pub industry, announced that some of its frozen burgers supplied by Silvercrest tested positive for horse DNA.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] A spokesman said that Makro no longer sells the product in question.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 14 February 2013, the French government stated that a French meat-processing company, À la Table de Spanghero, had knowingly sold horse meat labelled as beef, and that its licence was suspended while an inquiry was underway.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Spanghero imported meat from Romania and sold it on to another French company, Comigel, which made frozen ready meals at its factory in Luxembourg.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] French Consumer Affairs Minister Benoît Hamon said the meat had left Romania clearly and correctly labelled as horse and that it was afterwards that it was relabelled as beef by Spanghero.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The investigation also said some blame may rest with Comigel, claiming the staff there should have noticed anomalies in the paperwork, and realised from the smell and look of the meat once it was defrosted that it was not beef.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 7 February 2013, Findus announced that in a sample of 18 beef lasagne products that it tested, 11 contained between 60% and 100% horse meat.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] It was also revealed that some of the products sold had minced meat declared as beef that was 60–100% horse meat.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The source of the horse meat was third party supplier Comigel, a French-headquartered frozen ready meal producer, from its subsidiary Tavola factory in Capellen, Luxembourg.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] According to the FSA, the company had been alerted by a third-party French supplier on 4 February 2013, and it tested its beef lasagne products, finding that over 50% of the products tested contained horse meat.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] According to reports, both Findus UK and the French supplier withdrew all products related to the third-party supplier.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The reason for the adulteration was initially stated as "highly likely" criminal activity.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The president of Comigel, Erick Lehagre, told Agence France-Presse that the adulterated meat supplier was Spanghero, a firm owned by Lur Berri and founded in 1970 by Claude and Laurent Spanghero, two former France international rugby players.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] He said that Spanghero had told him that the meat was not from France, but came from a producer in Romania.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 11 February 2013, France's Consumer Affairs Minister Benoit Hamon warned it "will not hesitate" to take legal action if there is evidence companies had knowingly duped consumers.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Hamon said an initial investigation by French safety authorities had found that a French company, Poujol (Spanghero's holding company), had bought frozen meat from a Cypriot trader.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] That trader had bought it from Dutch food supplier Draap (the Dutch word for horse, *paard*, spelled backwards), owned by Jan Fasen, who was previously convicted in 2012 of horsemeat fraud dating back to 2007.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Draap, in turn, bought it from two Romanian slaughterhouses.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Poujol then supplied a factory in Luxembourg, owned by Comigel, which then supplied Findus and the British supermarkets.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The Romanian government has stated that there are no contracts between the Romanian abattoirs and any French, Cypriot, or Dutch meat processors.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 8 February 2013, Findus announced that it would no longer accept meat from Comigel and stopped further deliveries of the product in question.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On the same day, Findus UK published a public apology on its website, also announcing that, following DNA testing, three of its products were found to contain horse tissue.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] These are the 320, 350, and 500 gram packages of Findus Beef Lasagne; the company offered a refund for products purchased.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Findus Sverige AB also announced a recall of its 375 gram packs of ready-made single-portion lasagne (code 63957), and published a contact number for customers who had already purchased the products.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 8 February 2013, supermarket chain Aldi announced that it would withdraw from sale Today's Special Frozen Beef Lasagne and Today's Special Frozen Spaghetti Bolognese, supplied by Comigel, after tests found the meat content to be between 30 and 100% horse.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The Swiss-based company Nestlé reported on 18 February 2013 that it had found more than 1% horse DNA in two beef pasta products.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] It withdrew chilled pasta products, Buitoni Beef Ravioli and Beef Tortellini, in Italy and Spain.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Sourced from sub-contractor HJ Schypke, itself a German sub-contractor of Belgian-based Nestlé supplier JBS Toledo, also withdrew frozen Lasagnes à la Bolognaise Gourmandes, a product for catering businesses produced in France.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 22 February 2013, Birds Eye revealed that DNA tests showed that horse meat was present in Birds Eye chili con carne sold in Belgium and supplied by Belgium firm Frigilunch.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Birds Eye withdrew three ready meals that contained beef from sale in the UK.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] All of the frozen beef products produced by Sodexo, "one of the largest private catering businesses in Britain", were withdrawn on 22 February 2013 following the discovery of horse DNA in a sample.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The company supplies 2,300 institutions within the UK, including schools, old-age people's homes, prisons, and branches of the armed forces.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 1 March, the Department of Food and Veterinary of Lithuania announced that horse meat was found in three canned beef brands sold by Latvian company Kuršu Zeme.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Canned beef made by the Latvian company was removed from sale in Lithuania.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 10 April 2013, it was reported that two Dutch trading companies, owned by the same person whom food safety officials had previously investigated, may have supplied 50,000 metric tonnes of adulterated beef containing horse meat since January 2011.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 7 February 2013, it was revealed by the Food Standards Agency that the Findus beef lasagne range in the UK, France, Norway, and Sweden, and the shepherd's pie and moussaka ranges in France, contained horse meat without proper declaration or official scrutiny.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The contamination may have gone on since summer 2012 according to a leaked document.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Compass Group was the world's biggest catering firm at the time and discovered through conducting tests that it was unknowingly supplying concealed horse meat in food products to a "small number" of schools in Northern Ireland.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Whitbread, which was at the time Britain's biggest hotel group, also discovered through tests that it had unknowingly sold concealed horse meat in food products.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The horse meat that was found in Comigel products originated at Doly Com, a Romanian-based slaughterhouse.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] An inquiry by the French government showed that "the meat had left Romania clearly and correctly labelled as horse.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] It was afterwards that it was relabelled as beef." Doly Com supplied the horse meat under a contract to Cyprus-based Draap Trading Ltd, a meat trader which operates in the Netherlands.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] It is owned by a British Virgin Islands holding company, and Jan Fasen is a director.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] *Draap* spelt backwards is *paard,* the Dutch word for *horse*.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] After having the horse meat delivered to a cold storage company in Breda, Draap then sold the frozen meat to Spanghero, who insist that it arrived at their Castelnaudary plant labelled as "Beef – originating in EU".
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] After some processing, Spanghero then sent it to Comigel, where the end products for sale were made.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] According to French media reports, Spanghero falsified documents regarding the meat.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Horse meat found in Silvercrest products is thought to have originated in Poland.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] A small survey, part of the EU-funded project FoodRisC, conducted by a team from University College Dublin and Brunel University found that health risks were not respondents' first concern; rather, the claims made on labels did not match the contents of food products.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Additional concerns included allegations that a "French plant which handled horse meat sold in Britain as beef has previously been at the centre of a major E.coli discovery".
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Inquiry into horse meat sources in the UK also revealed that Aintree racecourse has a contract with a licensed slaughterhouse in West Yorkshire to remove dead Grand National race horses.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] It is illegal for horses euthanised by injection to be put into the human food chain.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Many chemical agents used for animal euthanasia leave residues in the meat, which may be harmful to humans, and have caused sickness and death in predators and scavengers.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In January 2013, concerns first arose about the possibility that horse meat containing traces of the veterinary drug phenylbutazone could enter the human food chain, despite regulations that horses treated with it cannot legally be used for human consumption.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The drug, commonly known as "bute", is used as an analgesic in horses.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The issue was also raised by politicians such as Labour party MP Mary Creagh.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In response, the Food Standards Agency (FSA) initially stated that only five cases of horses slaughtered in the UK had been treated with phenylbutazone, none of which had entered the human food chain.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] A subsequent review of 206 horse carcasses slaughtered in the UK between 30 January and 7 February 2013 found eight were contaminated with phenylbutazone, six of which had been shipped to France.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The UK's Chief Medical Officer, Sally Davies, said the level of contamination, 1.9 mg/kg, posed "very little risk to human health".
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] She added that around 500–600 burgers containing 100% horse meat would need to be eaten to receive the daily human therapeutic dose.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Additional tests at that time indicated than none of the products from Findus contained phenylbutazone.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Another report found that between two and five percent of samples tested between 2007 and 2011 had phenylbutazone contamination, and that only 50 samples per year were tested.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In 2012, 145 carcasses were tested, and two of the nine carcasses that tested positive for bute that year were not reported to the FSA for seven months.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] However, one problem raised was over-documentation; all UK animals with phenylbutazone contamination tested in early 2013 possessed a "horse passport" that allowed their carcasses to be sold for human consumption.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The veterinary residues committee (VRC) reminded the public in July 2012 that it had been "repeatedly expressing concern" about phenylbutazone contamination. and recent discoveries of contamination suggest that the passport system was not working.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Phenylbutazone is used therapeutically in humans as a treatment for ankylosing spondylitis when other treatments are not suitable.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The effect on humans of low-level exposure over an extended period has not been extensively formally studied.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] High incidences of focal necrosis were found in female rats fed low doses of 1,2-diphenylhydrazine over time.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) residues risk causing rare, but potentially fatal side-effects in humans.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] There is inadequate data on carcinogenicity of phenylbutazone; it is not classifiable as to its carcinogenicity to humans.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] There is also speculation that some horse meat from the United States, where phenylbutazone is commonly used, may have entered the food chain via Mexico and then been exported to Europe.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] One reason for this is that Spanghero had purchased meat from a company, Draap, whose owner, Jan Fasen was previously convicted for fraud; as long ago as 2007, Draap had labelled horse meat imported from Mexico and South America as Dutch or German beef.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] These animals may have meat too toxic to eat safely.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Some experts and UK government officials have raised concerns that horse meat from Romania could be contaminated with equine infectious anaemia (EIA).
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Although EIA does not pose a risk to humans, it could be an indicator of additional health problems in horses that may stem from poor living conditions.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Since 2007, the European Union has restricted export of live horses from Romania to any other EU member state unless the animals have a Coggins test for EIA prior to export.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Environment secretary Owen Paterson stated that "Romanian horse meat is not allowed in", though he acknowledged that it could be a serious problem if Romanian horse meat from animals with EIA had been imported.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Some news outlets referred to EIA as "Horse AIDS", even though it is not an immunodeficiency syndrome and the retrovirus that causes it is equid-specific.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] EIA is, however, a lentivirus, like HIV, and thus research on EIA has the potential to help research efforts with HIV/AIDS.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] An article by Will Hutton about contamination in the UK lays much of the responsibility at the door of those who have removed much of the regulation of the meat industry, and cut the budgets and workforces—halving the number of inspectors—of those responsible for enforcing the remaining regulations.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Another article points out that "Long business supply chains are corruptible and can hide a multitude of crimes if no one checks for fraud or criminal activity".
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In Britain, the incident was a catalyst for the discussion of the validity of a self-regulated meat industry.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Karen Jennings, assistant general secretary of the UNISON trades union, said that "the industry isn't fit to regulate itself".
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Observant Muslims and Jews consider it sinful to eat certain types of meat, pork for both groups, and also horse and many other animals for Jews, due to religious prohibitions.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Professor Reilly stated "for some religious groups or people who abstain from eating pig meat, the presence of traces of pig DNA is unacceptable".
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 15 March 2013, a Westminster health and safety survey confirmed that pig DNA had been found in halal chicken sausages produced for schools.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Horse meat is not normally eaten in Ireland and Britain.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] According to Professor Reilly, chief executive of the FSAI, "In Ireland, it is not our culture to eat horse meat and therefore, we do not expect to find it in a burger".
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Silvercrest, a subsidiary of ABP Foods has claimed that there is no risk to the public upon eating the foreign meat.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Eleven firms, including Tesco and Asda, said they shared shoppers' "anger and outrage".
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Whitbread vowed to remedy the unacceptable situation.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The Food Standards Agency's (FSA) chief executive, Catherine Brown also said "it is unlikely we will ever know" how many unwittingly ate horsemeat.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Tesco's market value dropped by €360 million.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] European Union officials, European ministers and Commissioner (Tonio) Borg set up an urgent meeting in Brussels on 13 February 2013 on how to contain the horse meat scandal that exposed flaws in European control systems on food safety, and to formulate an action plan.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Following the meeting, EU agriculture ministers announced a three-month coordinated control plan of DNA testing of processed meat across the European Union.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The plan, adopted 19 February 2013, called for 2,500 random tests on processed food for horse DNA and 4,000 for phenylbutazone (bute), beginning in March 2013, with initial results announced on 15 April 2013.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The Hague-based Europol would handle the co-ordination of investigations among national authorities, as well as any raids on premises and arrests on suspicion of criminal conspiracy to defraud.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 26 February 2013, it was announced that sales of frozen hamburgers had fallen by 43% and frozen ready meals by 13% from pre-scandal levels.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] The study took place 21 January – 17 February.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Sales of *bona fide* horse meat, on the other hand, increased in those EU countries where it is moderately common.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 23 May 2013, a Dutch meat wholesaler, Willy Selten, was arrested for allegedly selling 300 tonnes of horsemeat as beef.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] Selten, who owns the meat wholesaler Willy Selten BV, was arrested together with the company's interim director.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In October, Barry Gardiner MP, the UK shadow Environment minister, criticised the lack of prosecutions of leading players ten months after David Cameron had promised that everything possible would be done to deal with a "very shocking" crime.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 26 August 2016, Andronicos Sideras, owner of Dinos and Sons Ltd, was charged with conspiring with Ulrich Nielsen and Alex Ostler-Beech, of Flexi Foods, to sell horsemeat as beef between 1 January 2012 – 31 October 2012 by the City of London Police.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] On 2 August 2017 Sideras was jailed for four years and six months and Nielsen for three years and six months, while Ostler-Beech was given an 18-month suspended sentence and a 120 hour-community service order.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] In December 2013, consignments of horse meat were seized, and arrests were made.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] 21 people were arrested on Monday, 16 December, in various parts of southern France.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] This meat was from horses kept on a farm attached to a scientific laboratory and not certified as fit for human consumption.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/2013-horse-meat-scandal] A dealer from Narbonne was helping police with enquiries.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/3g-capital] The firm is best known for its long-term investments in Anheuser-Busch InBev, Restaurant Brands International (Burger King, Tim Hortons, Firehouse Subs, and Popeyes Louisiana Kitchen), Hunter Douglas, Kraft Heinz, and Skechers, as well as partnering with Berkshire Hathaway for its acquisitions.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/3g-capital] In 2010, the company acquired Burger King for $3.3 billion, and subsequently took the company private.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/3g-capital] In June 2012, Burger King was once again listed as a publicly traded company through a $1.4 billion deal with Justice Holdings.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/3g-capital] Despite the relisting, 3G Capital retained a 71% stake of the company.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/3g-capital] In December 2014, the Canadian government approved the purchase of Tim Hortons by 3G Capital for $12.5 billion, creating Restaurant Brands International (RBI), the world's third-largest quick service restaurant company.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/3g-capital] In March 2015, 3G Capital partnered with Warren Buffett to acquire Kraft Foods for $40 billion, and merged it with Heinz to form the world's fifth largest food company.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/3g-capital] In June 2021, Kraft Heinz acquired Assan Foods, a Turkish company focused on sauces, for approximately $100 million.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/3g-capital] In September 2021, Kraft Heinz acquired Hemmer, a Brazilian company focused on condiments and sauces.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/3g-capital] In 2017, RBI acquired Popeyes Louisiana Kitchen, Inc. for $1.8 billion.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/3g-capital] In 2021, RBI acquired Firehouse Restaurant Group Inc. for $1.0 billion in 2021.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/3g-capital] 3G Capital Co-Managing Partner Daniel Schwartz, who also served as CFO, COO, and CEO at different times, is credited for turning around Burger King and later growing the Restaurant Brands International holding group.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/3g-capital] In December 2021, it was announced that 3G Capital was acquiring a 75% stake in Hunter Douglas, a window coverings and architectural products manufacturer.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/3g-capital] The deal was completed in February 2022, and 3G Capital Partner, João Castro Neves, was appointed Hunter Douglas Group CEO.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/3g-capital] In the fourth quarter of 2023, 3G Capital divested its 16.1% stake in Kraft Heinz.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/3g-capital] In May 2025, 3G Capital acquired Skechers for $9.42 bn.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/advertising-age] The site AdCritic.com was acquired by The Ad Age Group in March 2002.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/advertising-age] In 2004, *Advertising Age* acquired *American Demographics* magazine.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/advertising-age] In 2007 Ad Age acquired the Thoddands Power 150, which is a top marketing blogs list.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/advertising-age] An industry trade magazine, *BtoB*, was folded into *Advertising Age* in January 2014.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/advertising-age] In 2017, the magazine shortened its name to *Ad Age*.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/advertising-age] In 1980, Henderson Advertising, founded in 1946 by James M.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/advertising-age] Henderson in Greenville, South Carolina, became the first agency outside New York or Chicago to be named Advertising Age's "Advertising Agency of the Year".
[src:bk-chicken-fries/advertising-age] Since 2016, Ad Age has been running an annual award called **Creativity 50** honoring the 50 most creative people in the advertising, marketing, technology and entertainment industries, in addition to top creative campaigns and the most innovative advertising.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/advertising-age] Past winners have also included entertainers such as Beyonce, David Bowie, Sia, Dwayne Johnson, James Corden, Donald Glover, Stephen Colbert and author Kelly Oxford.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/advertising-age] In June 1968, the magazine's editorial board generated controversy and significant discussion about gun control in the United States after it ran an editorial with the headline "Guns Must Go".
[src:bk-chicken-fries/advertising-age] The editorial was written in response to the assassination of Robert F.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/advertising-age] Immense reaction generated after its publication, including fierce backlash.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/advertising-age] The magazine's managing editor, Jarlath J.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/advertising-age] Graham, soon remarked that "all hell broke loose" after the publication of the editorial.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] AmRest is listed on the Warsaw Stock Exchange since 2005 and Madrid Stock Exchange since 2018 with Mexican investor Carlos Fernández González as majority stakeholder.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] Eisenbeiss established **American Restaurants Services**.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] Initially, the company held franchise rights to operate Pizza Hut and KFC restaurants in western Poland.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In 1998, it expanded its operations outside Poland, by taking over KFC and Pizza Hut locations in the Czech Republic which were previously run by Yum!
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In 2000, AmRest Holdings was formed as a joint venture company between American Restaurants and Yum!
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] Brands, and in 2001 the new company took over **International Fast Food Polska**, the operator of the Burger King locations in Poland.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] Out of the 23 Burger King restaurants acquired, the Company closed 6 and rebranded the remaining 17 into KFC.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In 2005, the company acquired the remaining franchise for Yum! concepts in the Czech Republic and Poland becoming the exclusive KFC and Pizza Hut franchisee in those countries.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In 2006 AmRest bought the rights to seventeen KFC and Pizza Hut restaurants in Hungary and launched new Freshpoint and Rodeo Drive brands.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] AmRest debuted on the stock market in April 2005 and Yum exited the company as a shareholder.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In May 2005 AmRest acquired 8 Big Food restaurants in Czech Republic, and rebranded them into KFC.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In 2007 AmRest opened its first new Burger King restaurant in Poland, the first KFC restaurants in Serbia and Bulgaria and signed joint venture agreements with Starbucks about opening the coffee chain's stores in Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In 2008 company signed agreements about opening Burger King in Bulgaria and acquired several restaurants in Russia.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In January 2008 AmRest opened first Starbucks store in Prague.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] The company opened its first Starbucks location in Poland in 2008.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In May 2008, AmRest acquired 80% shares in Apple Grove Holding, the second biggest Applebee's franchisee in the United States.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In April 2010, Warburg Pincus, a premier private equity firm, offered to invest over 300 million pln for a 24.99% shareholding in AmRest.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In 2010, AmRest also opened the first Starbucks in Hungary.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In April 2011 AmRest announced the acquisition of Spanish company Restauravia, operating 30 KFC's and over 120 Italian Casual Dining restaurants La Tagliatella.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] La Tagliatella was announced to be one of the main drivers of AmRest's global expansion.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] But the result of AmRest's attempts since 2012 for developing La Tagliatella chain of restaurants outside Spain was without success.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] Locations opened in China, India and the United States closed quickly.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] The subsidiary in France, which operates the group's five restaurants, generated a loss of 2.9 million euros in 2017, a total of 11.7 million euros since 2012.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] AmRest LLC, which operated 102 Applebee's restaurants in the United States was sold to American Apple Group, the largest franchisee of Applebee's on June 7, 2012.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] On December 14, 2012, AmRest acquired Blue Frog and Kabba restaurant brands in China.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] AmRest has increased the number of countries in which it operates Starbucks after acquiring the coffee shops operated by Greek Marinopoulos Coffee in Romania and Bulgaria in March 2015.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In April 2016, AmRest also bought 144 Starbucks coffee shops in Germany for 41 million euros.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In 2017, the company moved its headquarters from Poland to Madrid, Spain.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] AmRest acquired the Sushi Shop restaurant chain in France in July 2018.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] Burger King returned to Slovakia after AmRest opened a restaurant in November 2018.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In April 2019, AmRest opened the first Starbucks cafe in Serbia.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] It also returned Burger King in Romania by opening first restaurants in Bucharest, after 7 years break, in which only the airport location was operated.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/amrest] In March 2022, Amrest suspended its operations in Russia due to the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine; in 2023, the company sold its Russia-based KFC business to Russian franchise holder Smart Service for at least 100 million euros.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] As one of the company's major offerings, the chicken fries are sometimes the center of product advertising for the company.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] With the product's North American reintroduction in 2014 and 2015, Burger King utilized a heavy social media campaign to help entice fans of the product back into restaurants.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The company has also relied heavily on product tie-ins with the NFL, NCAA and NASCAR to promote the product across different demographic groups.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Even though the product has been a prominent part of the menu for the better part of a decade, Burger King has released very few LTO variants of the product, with the first one being released in the summer of 2015.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Despite being a major product line in the company's portfolio, Burger King has registered very few, if any, global trademarks to protect its investment in the product.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] BK Chicken Fries were introduced in 2005 as part of a menu expansion that was designed to cater to a more adult demographic looking for dishes that went beyond the standard fast food fare.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] At the time of the introduction, Burger King was targeting a demographic group it identified as the "super fan", a group consisting of males between the ages of 18 and 34 that ate at fast food restaurants several times a week.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Additionally, the chain was also adding other fare such as its TenderGrill, TenderCrisp and Angus sandwiches, that were designed to offer more complex menu items that would raise average check prices and expand the breadth of its offerings in the fast food market place.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The product was discontinued in January 2012, replaced with Burger King's version of chicken strips in March of that year.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Following Chicken Fries' discontinuation, there was a call for the product's reinstatement from fans of the product on forums such as Reddit; Business Insider noted that they are one of the 17 most requested fast products that people would like to see returned to menus.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Fans of the product also established several social media accounts dedicated to Chicken Fries' return on Facebook, Twitter, and Tumblr.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Additionally, a Change.org petition was created that called on Burger King to reinstate the product to its menu.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Perez Hilton's web site declared that Chicken Fries are one product of many that will never come back, while comedian Daniel Tosh featured a skit during one of the segments of his show, Tosh.0, to the product's return.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] They were re-released in August 2014 as a limited time offering (LTO).
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The return of the product met with a favorable reaction from those who were advocating for Chicken Fries to return to the Burger King menu.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] There was disappointment from these groups as well because of the product's status as a limited time offering.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] In March 2015, Burger King permanently re-added Chicken Fries to the menu in a large, international menu expansion in thirty countries.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The product received large amounts of attention on the internet after its discontinuation; at its peak the product was being mentioned in one form or another on average once every 40 seconds.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] In its third-quarter 2014 earnings report, Burger King admitted that the massive social media attention was one of the primary reasons it brought the product back.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The positive reaction to the reintroduction included over one million mentions on Twitter.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] This tied into a major push by the company to utilize social media as a free marketing tool to millennials, who overwhelmingly utilize interactive media to communicate and prefer companies that utilize these tools.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Besides customer demand for the product, another major reason for the reintroduction was due to a significant rise in the cost of beef.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] During the previous few months leading up to the reintroduction of Chicken Fries, the available cattle stocks had declined since the USDA began record keeping in 1973.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] This shortage of ground beef caused a spike in the price of beef to all-time highs in June 2014, according to the Bureau of Labor Statistics.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Additionally, increasing competition from McDonald's, Wendy's and other chains in the fast food industry drove Burger King to boost sales by introducing new products along similar lines.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Two major competitors had been revamping their menus with products such as variations on the McDouble from McDonald's and sandwiches based on pretzel-style buns from Wendy's.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The limited-time offers allow chains to bring "new" product the menu without adding permanent complexity to their kitchen operations.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The reintroduction of Chicken Fries proved to be a fortuitous decision for Burger King, the resulting sales bump provided an increase in profits each time they were added to the menu.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The 2014 reintroduction was a resounding success for the company, helping Burger King achieve domestic same-store comparable sales rise of 3.1% in 2014.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Again, arch rival McDonald's reported that its same-store comparable sales fell 2% for the same time period in the US as its promotions failed to meet financial analysts' predictions.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] BK Chicken Fries are breaded and fried chicken strips, and were available in three sizes during their initial availability period: six-, nine-, and twelve-piece servings.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Three and thirty-six-piece sizes were available as limited time offers (LTO).
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The smaller size was sold à la carte, while larger portion could be purchased as a meal option.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] While its core audience was adults such as soccer moms or commuters, a kids' meal option was at one time available in the U.S. that included a six-piece order of the product.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The 2014 reissued product was only available in a nine-piece serving, at a recommended price point of USD $2.89.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] A summer 2015 LTO introduced a spicy variant, called Fiery Chicken Fries, in addition to the standard offering; the product featured a spicy breading featuring a mix of cayenne pepper, black pepper and other spices that replaced the normal coating.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The product was the first variant of BK Chicken Fries added to the company's menu.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] In developing the product, Burger King's chief marketing officer stated that once taste testers described the product as "spicy as shit", the company realized it had the correct spice mix.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Sale of the product would be limited to a one-month period, but the company stated if sales were successful enough it would consider extending the availability beyond the initial time frame.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] To accompany the 2015 re-introduction of the product, the chain released a new sauce simply called Chicken Fry Sauce.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The new condiment was not widely advertised, with almost all promotion being done through the company's social media accounts on Twitter and Facebook.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The sauce is described as a combination of BBQ sauce and honey mustard, and described by Burger King as "the sauce of all sauces." The company's posts were accompanied by the hashtag #AskForTheSauce.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Part of the product's format was in its packaging, which was designed to fit in a car cup holder.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The BK Chicken Fry box, while square in shape, will sit comfortably in the cup holder and its top, when opened, forms a small tray that is designed to hold dipping sauce.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Burger King credits the design of this box with helping to make its Chicken Fries the most popular adult-oriented chicken product in the United States at the time.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Since most of the fast food industry's business is take-out or drive-thru traffic, this allowed the convenience food purchaser to drive and eat with little effort.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] With the introduction of the BK Chicken Fries, BK began adapting some of its other product packaging so that it could also be placed in an automotive cup holder.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] In addition to the Chicken Fries container, the company added a trademarked and patented, round French fry container which it calls the "FryPod", which is a paper cup made from 50 percent recycled materials that is also designed to fit in an automotive cup holder.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The package design won an honorable mention at a packaging industry design competition hosted by the Quick Service Restaurant division of the Foodservice and Packaging Institute in 2007.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The 2015 Fiery Chicken Fries promotion introduced a packaging variant that featured new graphics.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The image featured on the box is an angry looking chicken in a Lucha libre-style mask.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Other packaging variants that have appeared over the years have included tie-ins to the NFL and SpongeBob SquarePants.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] According to CP+B employee Tom Zukoszki, the fictional background information for the band was that they signed with Burger King instead of a major record label.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] As part of the promotion, a four-song LP record was recorded, two music videos produced, and a national (US) tour planned.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The tour had to be cancelled because the actor playing the lead singer, a Canadian citizen, was unable to enter the United States because he had a criminal record in his home country.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The 2014 reintroduction of the product featured a first for the company, a primarily digital-focused promotion headed by the company's online media agency Code and Theory.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] To start off the promotion, the company announced the forthcoming reintroduction a few weeks before the product was set to be released with the simple tweet "You asked.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] We answered. #ChickenFriesAreBack." The company also expanded its social media footprint specifically for the Chicken Fries promotion, adding new Tumblr and Snapchat accounts to their stable of social media outlets.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The idea behind the large social media push was monetary, instead of spending capital on a traditional multi-week, multi-media advertising campaign the company would have product-loyalists spread the word at a fraction of the cost of traditional advertising.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Instead of producing a new series of spots on the television front, the chain reused the commercials originally produced by Crispin, Porter + Bogusky from the initial product run.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] These commercials were only played on Thursdays, specifically for the social media meme known as Throwback Thursday, events that feature historical personal stories or happenings that are routinely run on various sites such as Facebook or Instagram.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The only major change to the advertisements was the addition of the hashtag #TBT to the lower left-hand corner of the video.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] After the end of the promotional period, Burger King received numerous complaints from fans of Chicken Fries through social media sites such as Twitter and Facebook.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] One of the major ways the company responded was through personalized responses to these posts.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Instead of using an automated response that would paste a standardized message on people's Twitter feeds, the company instead employed several staff to personally respond to customers voicing displeasure on the LTO nature of the 2014 introduction.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The entire 2014 Chicken Fries promotion represented a major shift in the attitude towards advertising for Burger King, moving from a more traditional advertising structure to one focused almost entirely on digitally based media.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] This change happened fairly quickly, falling into place over the twelve to eighteen-month period preceding the reintroduction of Chicken Fries to the chain's menu.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Along with the new advertising firm, a new director of digital marketing and social media was newly hired from cosmetics firm L'Oréal was added, increasing the clout of the digital advertising team within the chain.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Advertising for the permanent reintroduction of Chicken Fries in early 2015 was again shaped around a large digital-media push headed by its new advertising firm David.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] However, unlike the 2014 promotion that was almost exclusively digitally oriented, the 2015 promotion was accompanied with a sizable television and media tie-in to the annual NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship tournament.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] In the host city of Indianapolis, Burger King sponsored Chicken Fries-branded SUVs that would give free rides to visitors.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] A series of advertisements for the product and the company's 2 for $5 sandwich promotion ran during the tournament featuring the hash tag #WatchLikeaKing, along with a series of NCAA co-branded kid's meals.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] On the digital front, the company utilized a viral marketing strategy starring a chicken named Gloria.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Gloria would be brought to local restaurants to decide if the particular location would sell Chicken Fries that day; she would be given two feed bowls labeled "yes" and "no" and depending on which bowl she ate from would decide if the product would be sold there that day.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Gloria the chicken had her own truck with her own custom-designed coop.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] There was a social media presence accompanying the tour with the hashtags #RandomGloria and #ChickenFries.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Additionally, each of the events were live streamed on the product's webpage, which also included other things such as Gloria's biography, a map of upcoming events and links to corporate web sites.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The Gloria tour did raise the ire of animal rights organization PETA.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The group initially responded to the promotion with a one-word tweet, "DESPICABLE," with the follow-up "@BurgerKing forcing a chicken to decide if her friends will become #ChickenFries." PETA stated that the concept behind the tour made their jaws drop over perceived cruelty.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The CP+B produced Coq Roq advertisements followed a pattern of controversy for the company, as previous advertisements produced by CP+B had come under fire for perceived or overt sexual innuendo.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The issues raised by public interest groups in this instance came from complaints over the double entendres and sexual innuendo on the Coq Roq website.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Pictures of scantily clad women posing as groupies of the band were featured in one section of the site and sported comments such as "groupies love the Coq" and "Groupies love Coq".
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Protests from the public over the sexual innuendo of the comments forced BK to request CB+P to have content be changed to something more appropriate for a family oriented restaurant.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] In August 2005, CP+B and Burger King became the target of lawyers of the band Slipknot, who alleged the mask-wearing rooster rockers were a blatant copy of the band's style.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The band claimed that CP+B had approached Slipknot's record company, Roadrunner Records, with an offer to appear in another commercial for Burger King.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The band declined on the grounds that they did not want to be associated with a burger chain and they felt that the Coq Roq advertisements were deliberately co-opting the band's signature look and style in order to influence its fans to purchase the chain's products.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The band issued a cease and desist letter to CP+B and BK requesting the advertisements be pulled.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] When the two parties declined, the band sued for an undisclosed amount.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Partly mentioned in the counter-suit included the notion that Slipknot were parodies of bands themselves, further citing the specific example of Mushroomhead, who wore near identical style masks and jumpsuits, and had been playing several years before Slipknot even formed, let alone went mainstream.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Both suits were eventually dropped, and Burger King ended the campaign shortly after.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] As a product tie-in with the 2005–2006 NFL season, Burger King introduced a 36 piece party pack as a limited time offer.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] This promotion was more general and featured the BK mascot, the Burger King, digitally superimposed into NFL game footage so appeared to be involved in the game.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Some of the players the King replaced include Steve Young, Deion Sanders, and Moe Williams.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] He has also been depicted performing the Lambeau Leap and dumping Gatorade on the head of former Miami Dolphins head coach Don Shula.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The primary packaging was altered to include the NFL logo; the party pack designed to mimic the texture of a football, included the NFL logo and a humorous comment along the line of those found on BK packaging at the time.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] During the summer of 2006, BK introduced the 12 piece size as a product tie-in with NASCAR and its new sponsorship of a NASCAR team.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] The promotion was part of the company's new sponsorship deal with NASCAR and the new BK/Michael Waltrip Racing team featuring Waltrip's 00 car number.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Several television ads were produced featuring BK Chicken Fries and Waltrip's racing team with a fictional pit crew member, the chicken server.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] During 2007, Burger King had another product tie-in with a Nickelodeon show, *SpongeBob SquarePants*.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Again the box was altered, this time so the design of the box looked like the character SpongeBob.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] Later in-store promotions in the U.S. have urged customers to add a six-piece portion to their meal as a snack option.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-chicken-fries] In Canada, "chicken fries" was owned by KFC parent Yum!
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-dinner-baskets] Also, complimentary popcorn was given to customers to eat while waiting for their meal to be brought to their table.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-dinner-baskets] The campaign was created by New York based agency D'Arcy Masius Benton & Bowles.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-dinner-baskets] The original ads were used to promote the Burger King Every Day Value Menu and Burger King Dinner Baskets.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-dinner-baskets] The advertising program was designed as part of a back to basics plan by Burger King after a series of disappointing advertising schemes including the failure of its 1980s *Where's Herb?* campaign.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-dinner-baskets] One of the main parts of the plan was to introduce a value menu in response to McDonald's, Taco Bell and Wendy's.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-dinner-baskets] Many of the ads featured Dan Cortese as Dan the Whopper Man, while others included featured clips from rap music artists Kid 'n Play's film *House Party*.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-dinner-baskets] The cross-promotion of the Disney film *Aladdin* was also advertised under this promotion, as well as *Last Action Hero*.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-dinner-baskets] The last commercials using this campaign was when it promoted *The Nightmare Before Christmas*.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] The **BK Stacker** sandwiches are a family of cheeseburgers sold by the international fast-food restaurant chain Burger King.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] In 2002, Burger King changed ownership when its parent company, Diageo, sold its interest in the company to a group of investment firms led by TPG Capital.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] After assuming ownership, TPG's newly appointed management team began focusing menu development and advertising on a very narrow demographic group, young men aged 20–34 who routinely ate at fast food restaurants several times per month which the chain identified as the "super fan".
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] Amid this new super-fan focused menu expansion the chain introduced its new **BK Stacker** sandwich in late 2006, a family of sandwiches featuring the same set of toppings served as a single, double, triple or quadruple hamburger.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] The Stacker line was part of a series of larger, more calorie-laden products introduced by the company to entice the super-fan into the chain's restaurants.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] These new additions helped propel same store profits for more than sixteen quarters.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] The Stacker consisted of anywhere from one to four 1.7 oz (48 g) beef patties, American cheese, bacon and a Thousand Island dressing variant called Stacker sauce served on a sesame seed bun.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] The new sandwiches had a muted reaction in several reviews—Chowhound.com readers rated the Quad Stacker as one of the most over-the-top gluttonous burgers in a poll, while the Impulsive Buy stated that the sandwich was much like any other bacon cheeseburger but meatier.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] Despite its lukewarm reception, an internet meme relating to the sandwich developed rather quickly.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] Customers would create an "Octo-Stacker" sandwich by purchasing two quad Stackers and mashing the two together sandwiches to create a sandwich with eight patties, eight slices of cheese and sixteen half pieces of bacon.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] They would then film themselves trying to eat the 1 lb (0.45 kg) sandwich in under five minutes.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] The Stacker line underwent a minor reformulation in 2011 that involved deleting the top layer of cheese and changing the amount of bacon in the sandwiches, and moving the sandwiches from the core section of its menu to the company's value menu.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] The changed ingredient list and pricing structure created a situation such that the distribution of ingredients did not scale at the same rate as increasing numbers of burger patties.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] Consumer Reports' blog The Consumerist noted that two single Stackers at $1.00 included more cheese and more bacon than one double Stacker for $2.00.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] Three single Stackers had 50% more cheese and double the bacon of one triple Stacker.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] The Stacker line and other related calorie-heavy menu items were dropped in 2012 when 3G Capital of Brazil bought the company and initiated a menu restructuring focusing on a broader demographic base.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] Since then, the Stacker line has been reintroduced under their 2005-2011 formulation and with a new name: the "Stacker King" sandwiches.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] Canadian locations serve both the 2005 formulations of the Stacker sandwiches as well as the 2011 formulations together.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] The 2005 formulations are branded as the "Stacker King" line, while the 2011 formulations are branded as simply the "Stacker" line.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] The BK Stacker is a hamburger consisting of anywhere from one to four 2.0 ounces (57 g) grilled beef patties, American cheese, bacon and Stacker sauce (a Thousand Island dressing variant) served on a sesame seed bun.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] The BK Stacker was introduced using commercials that employed groups of little people in the roles of members of the "Stackers Union".
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] The characters were "Vin," played by Danny Woodburn, "the new guy," and various members of the "Stackers Union" construction team that work in a BK kitchen assembling the sandwiches.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] The tag line was "Meat, Cheese and Bacon- Stacked High".
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-stacker] As exemplified in the advertising campaign, part of the sandwich's concept revolves around not having vegetables like lettuce, onions, or tomatoes.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-tee-vee] The campaign was created by the New York based agency D'Arcy Masius Benton & Bowles.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-tee-vee] The original advertisements were used to promote the Burger King Every Day Value Menu and BK Dinner Baskets.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-tee-vee] The advertising program was designed as part of a back to basics plan by Burger King after a series of disappointing advertising schemes, including the failure of its 1980s *Where's Herb?* campaign.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-tee-vee] Many of the advertisements featured Dan Cortese as Dan the Whopper Man, while others used clips from the rap musicians Kid 'n Play's film *House Party*.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-tee-vee] The last commercials using this campaign were to promote *The Nightmare Before Christmas*.
[src:bk-chicken-fries/bk-tee-vee] The advertisement program was also used in the German market to promote a sandwich called the Big Tex.
